(11, 'Differences to learn between ABN and TFN as an International Student in Australia', 'Differences to learn between ABN and TFN as an International Student in Australia', 'According to the Australian Taxation Office (ATO), an ABN (Australian Business Number) is a unique 11-digit identifier that makes it easier for businesses to', 'Differences to learn between ABN and TFN as an International Student in Australia', NULL, 0, '<p><strong>What is ABN?</strong></p><p>According to the Australian Taxation Office (ATO), an ABN (Australian Business Number) is a unique 11-digit identifier that makes it easier for businesses to connect. It’s a tax identification number for firms, freelancers, and contractors. Although this identification number is uncommon among international students, it is necessary to know it if someone wishes to work in their spare time. Not everyone is eligible for an ABN, but after you complete the process through the ATO’s website, it will tell you if you are. If students work for themselves and are paid by invoice, they will require this. To obtain an ABN, students must submit an application to the Australian Business Register (ABR) or through a Tax consultant. If all of the essential information is presented and the applicant is eligible for an ABN, he will receive his ABN number immediately after completing the application procedure. However, if there is missing or unconfirmed information, it may be necessary to process the material manually, which might take up to 28 days.</p><p><strong>What is TFN?</strong></p><p>TFN (Tax File Number) is a one-of-a-kind number used to identify a taxpayer. Everyone operating on behalf of an employer in Australia must have a TFN number. It allows companies to deduct tax from employees’ wages under the PAYG (Pay As You Go) system, and it also allows employees to reclaim some of that tax when filing their taxes. It’s wise to apply for it as soon as possible because the Australian government gets up to 28 days to provide the applicant with his unique TFN number. If they have a TNF number, people won’t have to worry about having a tax liability at the end of the year.</p><p><i><strong>Note: </strong>Avoid working more than 20 hours per week (apart from during university holidays). Less is better. Alternatively, students may face expulsion from the country.</i></p><p><strong>Differences between TFN and ABN.</strong></p><p>Working with a Tax File Number (TFN) implies that their employer will withhold tax from each payment and make payments to their superannuation. All individuals working in Australia must have a Tax File Number to pay their taxes on time. When someone changes jobs or starts working for a new company, they need the TFN number in the formal employment paperwork. It also covers Worker’s Compensation Insurance in case of a workplace injury.</p><p>&nbsp;On the other hand, working with an ABN means that the employer is not required to withhold tax and is not required to pay superannuation. Self-employed individuals must have an ABN number for the tax process. They must themselves deduct taxes and declare them within the timeframe specified by the Australian tax authority. And because in ABN, no tax is deducted at the point of sale, the person who issues the invoice and receives the payment is receiving full payment for the items or services. However, a portion of that revenue should be kept to cover the tax liability at the end of the fiscal year.</p><p>People with a TFN pay their taxes at the time of payment. In contrast, business owners and freelancers with an ABN pay their taxes at the end of the fiscal year, which necessitates keeping track of their business operations and invoices to file appropriately.</p><p><strong>How to apply for ABN</strong></p><p>There are two primary methods for applying:</p><ul><li>Online through the Business Registration Service – it’s free.</li><li>&nbsp;Through a tax agent – they may charge a fee.</li></ul><p>There is a range of documents noncitizen applicants will require for the application process, and it’s easier if they already have a TFN number.&nbsp;</p><p>Some of the documents they would require:</p><ul><li>Foreign birth certificate</li><li>Foreign passport</li><li>Government identification</li><li>National photo identification or driver’s license</li></ul><p><strong>How to apply for TFN</strong></p><p>Applicants can apply for a free TNF number online through the Australia Taxation Office (ATO). But for non citizen there’s a bunch of conditions that needs to be met which includes:&nbsp;</p><ol><li>Being a foreign passport holder, permanent migrant, or temporary visitor&nbsp;</li><li>Already in Australia ( can’t apply before arrival)</li><li>Have a VISA in one of the following categories,&nbsp;</li></ol><ul><li>Permanent migrant VISA</li><li>A VISA with working rights</li><li>An overseas student VISA</li><li>A VISA allows you to stay in Australia indefinitely.</li></ul><p>The information requested will be:&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Passport or travel document number</li><li>Country of origin as it appears in your passport</li><li>Name as it appears in your passport</li><li>Other names, if applicable</li><li>Information about your partner</li><li>Your address and zip code</li><li>Contact information (Phone number and email)</li></ul>', 'differences-to-learn-between-abn-and-tfn-as-an-international-student-in-australia', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1658997938_722105.png', 1, '2022-07-28 18:45:39', '2022-07-28 18:45:39'),
(12, 'Driving in Australia as an International Student', 'Driving in Australia as an International Student', 'The basics of driving in Australia are no different from the rest of the world. Here anyone operating a car must have a valid driverâ€™s license. This', 'Driving in Australia as an International Student', NULL, 0, '<h4>Indtroduction</h4><p>The basics of driving in Australia are no different from the rest of the world. Here anyone operating a car must have a valid driver’s license. This includes international students and anyone else who is just here for a short time.</p><p>To guarantee the safety of people who drive and commute in a vehicle, Australia takes its traffic regulations very seriously. As a result, the penalties for driving without a legal license are severe.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Who needs to get a driver’s license in Australia</strong></p><p>If a visitor is on a student visa and has a valid overseas driver’s license, he does not need to obtain an NSW driver’s license as long as he meets the following criteria:</p><ul><li>He is still a visitor.</li><li>His international driver’s license is still valid and active.</li><li>He has not been banned or disqualified from driving in NSW or elsewhere.</li><li>His license has not been suspended or revoked, nor have his visiting driving privileges been revoked.</li></ul><p>Distinct states, however, have different legislation in this area. For example, if the international student’s studying in Victoria, he’ll need to convert his foreign driver’s license into a Victorian driver’s license within six months of arriving in the state. Furthermore, his license must be written in English or include an official English translation if it is not written in English.</p><p>Driving without a valid, approved driver’s license is a severe offense in any Australian state or territory. The following are the punishments in each state:</p><ul><li><i><strong>Victoria</strong></i> — depending on several criteria, the penalties can be very different. Drivers without a valid license, on the other hand, might face fines of up to $38,000 and prison sentences of up to two years!</li><li><i><strong>New South Wales </strong></i>– a fine of up to $5,500 and six to twelve months in prison are possible penalties in NSW.</li><li><i><strong>Queensland</strong></i> – Driving without a valid license in Queensland can result in a fine of up to $5,500 and a sentence of up to twelve months in prison.</li><li><i><strong>South Australia</strong></i> — The penalty in South Australia is a $2,500 fine, with reoffending resulting in a prison term.</li><li><i><strong>Western Australia</strong></i> — Driving without a license can result in fines of up to $600 and 18 months in prison in Western Australia.</li></ul><p><strong>Licensing in Australia</strong></p><p>Students must contact the applicable state body for driving and licensing to apply for an Australian driver’s license. This can be done online, in person, or over the phone. They’ll have to show up in person once they’ve scheduled an appointment to finish the test. A computer test on road rules and laws will be part of the driving test. They’ll also be required to take a driving test, if appropriate.</p><p>It’s a good idea to call one of the state licensing authorities and double-check the criteria in your situation, as they can be pretty complicated.</p><ul><li><i><strong>Australian Capital Territory </strong></i>— Road Transport Authority</li><li><i><strong>New South Wales </strong></i>— Roads and Maritime Services</li><li><i><strong>Northern Territory </strong></i>— Department of Transport</li><li><i><strong>Queensland</strong></i> — Department of Transport and Main Roads</li><li><i><strong>South Australia</strong></i> — Department of Planning, Transport, and Infrastructure</li><li><i><strong>Tasmania</strong></i> — Department of Infrastructure, Energy, and Resources</li><li><i><strong>Victoria </strong></i>— VicRoads</li><li><i><strong>Western Australia</strong></i> — Department of Transport&nbsp;</li></ul><p>The fees for each state or territory are as follows:&nbsp;</p><ul><li>New South Wales – $232</li><li>Victoria – $21</li><li>South Australia – $254</li><li>Western Australia – $133</li><li>Tasmania – $250</li><li>Queensland – $251</li><li>Northern Territory – $102</li><li>Australian Capital Territory – $232</li></ul><p>A temporary overseas visitor (i.e., not an Australian citizen and not a permanent resident of Australia) can apply for an NSW license if they are in NSW for more than three months.&nbsp;</p><p><i>Note: These licensing requirements do not apply to those already given an NSW license. People who transfer an Australian interstate or New Zealand license to an NSW license or visitors who do not have overseas permission apply for an NSW learner license.</i></p><p><strong>Buying a car</strong></p><p>For overseas students, purchasing, operating, and maintaining an automobile in Australia can be costly. It is not required to own a car in cities such as Brisbane, Sydney, or Melbourne because everyone in Australia has access to public transportation, making it simple to get around.</p><p>According to the RACV study from 2018, the average cost of owning, operating, and maintaining a car in Australia is AUD $10,894 per year and AUD$209.50 per week.</p><p>It’s also worth noting that overseas students are not permitted to take out loans, so you may need to find another source of income to cover the costs of purchasing and maintaining a vehicle.</p><p><strong>Car insurance process</strong></p><p>To drive in Australia, everyone must have car insurance to cover any costs that may arise from traffic incidents that damage their car or the automobile of another party or cause harm. In Australia, there are a few different forms of auto insurance to choose from:</p><ul><li>Compulsory third party insurance&nbsp;</li><li>Comprehensive insurance&nbsp;</li><li>Third-party property, theft, and fire insurance&nbsp;</li><li>Third-party property insurance</li></ul><p>CTP (Compulsory Third Party) Insurance is required while driving and registering an automobile in NSW. This insurance is also known as a ‘green slip,’ and there are no time extensions, so everyone must pay their CTP insurance fee when it is due. If they plan to drive in NSW, it is strongly advised that they additionally acquire third-party property damage or comprehensive insurance for their vehicle.</p><p><strong>Importance of road rules and laws of driving</strong></p><p>International students in Australia face some challenges when driving because they must be familiar with the country’s basic road rules. Here are some fundamental guidelines to follow:</p><ul><li>Always carry a driving license.&nbsp;</li><li>The driver, including the passengers, needs to wear safety belts in the car.</li><li>Littering and throwing anything out of the car is strictly prohibited.&nbsp;</li><li>Be cautious of speed limits and make sure to follow them.&nbsp;</li><li>Never use a mobile phone while driving.&nbsp;</li><li>Kids younger than seven years must be seated in their car seats.&nbsp;</li><li>Last but not least, don’t drink and drive.</li></ul><h4><strong>Conclution</strong></h4><p>It’s critical to understand our responsibilities for keeping our car or motorcycle roadworthy. Each state in Australia has its own set of rules, tests, and other requirements. However, their sole purpose is to determine whether or not someone can drive safely. The road rules in Australia are the most similar to those in New Zealand. Knowing the road regulations makes you a safer driver and contributes to the safety of other road users.</p><p>Every driver is allowed to accumulate a maximum of 12 demerit points on their license over three years. These demerit points are received for speeding, running a red light, talking on a cell phone while driving, and not wearing a seatbelt. If a person obtains 12 demerit points, their license will be suspended, and they will have to pay a hefty fee. In some areas, someone may even be sentenced to prison.</p>', 'driving-in-australia-as-an-international-student', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1658998209_304997.png', 1, '2022-07-28 18:50:09', '2022-07-28 18:50:09'),
(13, 'Complete Guide to Australian Skilled Nominated Visa Subclass 190', 'Complete Guide to Australian Skilled Nominated Visa Subclass 190', 'The Skilled Nominated visa (subclass 190) is a residency status skilled migration visa for professionals who have already lived and worked in Victoria and', 'Complete Guide to Australian Skilled Nominated Visa Subclass 190', NULL, 0, '<p>The Skilled Nominated visa (subclass 190) is a residency status skilled migration visa for professionals who have already lived and worked in Victoria and have skills that enhance Victoria’s health response and economic recovery. The Ministry of Home Affairs is in control of the visa.</p><p>One can work and study anywhere within Australia with this visa and sponsor qualifying relatives for permanent residency. Become an Australian citizen only if one has eligibility.</p><p><strong>Eligibility requirements for this visa&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Eligibility:</strong></p><p>If one has to be chosen to apply for a Skilled Nominated (subclass 190) visa, they must submit their visa nomination application through the Live-in Melbourne website. In addition, they must fulfill the following minimum eligibility requirements to be nominated for a Skilled Nominated (subclass 190) visa.</p><p><strong>Age requirements:</strong></p><p>To petition for the Skilled Nominated (subclass 190) visa, one must be fewer than 45.</p><p><strong>Language criteria:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Those applying for this visa must have a good command of the English language (or equivalent).</p><p>The proficient level is equivalent to at least six (6) points in each band of the International English Language Testing System (IELTS) or similar scores in authorized alternative examinations. In addition, applicants can acquire the IELTS equivalent in any of the Department of Home Affairs’ recognized language examinations, including the OET, TOEFL IBT, PTE Academic, and Cambridge English: Advanced (CAE).</p><p>As part of the online nomination application, applicants must attach a scanned copy of their English language exam results. When submitting a visa nomination application, applicants must guarantee that their English test result is valid for 12 weeks.</p><p><strong>Residency:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>&nbsp;To obtain a residency permit, one must have lived and worked in Victoria for at least the previous 6 months and then present proof of residency with the application form. As an example:</p><ul><li>A current commercial lease or bond arrangement</li><li>A bill or documents proving your continued residency in Victoria for the previous six months.</li></ul><p><strong>Finances:</strong></p><p>There are no financial limitations because all applicants must live and work in Victoria.</p><p><strong>Cost:</strong><br>The visa costs AUD 4045, spouse AUD 2025, and kid AUD 1010 (per child) — government fees do not include professional expenses.</p><p>Any candidate 18 years of age or older with less than functional English may be required to pay an additional fee. This charge is known as the second installment, and it must be spent only when requested. We only ask for the price if we intend to grant the visa.</p><p>For family members, the second installment fee is AUD4, 885.</p><p>The Visa Pricing Estimator does not include the second installment or any other fees, and you may be required to pay additional fees for health checks, police certificates, and biometrics.</p><p><strong>Apply from:</strong></p><p>When applying for this visa, the applicants can be inside or outside Australia.</p><p><strong>Processing times:</strong></p><p>We assess applications on a case-by-case basis, and actual processing times can vary due to individual circumstances, including:</p><ul><li>whether you have lodged a complete application, including all necessary supporting documents</li><li>how quickly do you respond to any requests for additional information</li><li>how long does it take to perform required checks on the supporting information provided</li><li>how long does it take to receive additional information from external agencies, particularly about health, character, and national security requirements</li><li>for permanent migration visa applications, how many places are available in the migration program</li></ul>', 'complete-guide-to-australian-skilled-nominated-visa-subclass-190', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1658998451_237903.png', 1, '2022-07-28 18:54:11', '2022-07-28 18:54:11'),
(14, 'The Pathway to Global Talent Visa', 'The Pathway to Global Talent Visa', 'Introduction', 'The Pathway to Global Talent Visa', NULL, 0, '<p><strong>Introduction</strong></p><p>One might be eligible for the Global Talent Visa if one wants to live and work in Australia. The visa is intended to encourage highly qualified, experienced, and exceptionally talented individuals to stay in Australia permanently. It is aimed at people who can exhibit relevant abilities in various health, technology, scientific, and financial fields.</p><p><strong>Global talent visa (GTI) program</strong></p><p>The Global Talent Visa Program is a simplified visa application process. It is for highly qualified people who want to work permanently and live in Australia. This program aims to bring highly trained and talented persons from specialized industries to Australia to settle permanently. Australia is seeking highly qualified and competent persons from all over the world in specified fields for priority processing to settle in Australia under the Global Talent Visa.</p><p>Australia is looking for the best and brightest global talent to work in eleven future-oriented industries. The program was created to help the economy by providing innovative skills to high-demand sectors. This will provide Australians with chances by:</p><ul><li>transferable abilities</li><li>encouraging innovation</li><li>job creation</li></ul><p><strong>How Does A Global Talent Visa Help?</strong></p><p>The Global Talent Independent Program (GTIP) is a permanent visa for those with a national or international record of exceptional and excellent success in a particular sector. Individuals who are well-known in their area and anticipated to earn at least $153,600 AUD in Australia are eligible for the program. The GTIP’s goal is to boost Australia’s innovation and tech economies while attracting top talent in key industries.</p><p>In the fiscal year 2020-2021, 15,000 spaces were made available under the program, which is three times the number available the previous year. This acknowledges the significant contribution that persons who already hold this visa or may be eligible to apply under the Global Talent visa have made to Australia.</p><p><strong>Benefits of a Global Talent Visa</strong></p><p>The Global Talent Visa is an incredibly appealing alternative over other permanent residency visas if you match the eligibility conditions (the skilled independent visa subclass 189 and 190, or employer-sponsored visa subclass 186). This is due to the following reasons:</p><ul><li>there is no requirement to provide a skills evaluation;</li><li>are not required to achieve a certain number of points;</li><li>are exempt from meeting basic English standards;</li><li>state or territory nominations or employer sponsorship are not necessary;</li><li>if they can demonstrate exceptional economic contribution to Australia, they can be up to 55 years old or older; and</li><li>a recent Ph.D. grad in one of the primary target industries</li></ul><p><strong>Eligibility Criteria</strong></p><p>The Global Talent Visa is an appealing choice for highly talented candidates who can demonstrate their international recognition and achievements. The following criteria are used to establish your visa eligibility. People:</p><ul><li>Having a track record of remarkable and excellent accomplishments that are recognized internationally;</li><li>Are you well-known in your area of competence;</li><li>It would be beneficial to Australia’s community;</li><li>Would have no trouble finding work or establishing yourself as an independent in Australia in your field of expertise;</li><li>Have a national reputation in the same field from an Australian organization or individual who can witness your achievements;</li><li>AUD $153,600 in present or projected income;</li><li>Fulfill the requirements for an onshore qualifying visa, including Schedule 3 (where applicable);&nbsp;</li><li>Make your application in one of the target sectors listed below or a similar industry.</li></ul><p><strong>Nomination For the Global Talent Visa</strong></p><p>When submitting your DTV application, you must choose a nominator and have them complete Form 1000. A nominator, for example, must be:</p><ul><li>Citizen of Australia;</li><li>Permanent resident of Australia;</li><li>A New Zealand citizen who qualifies; or</li><li>An Australian-based organization.</li></ul><p>For your application, only one nominator is required. If you submit multiple nominations, the Department may ask you to choose only one nominator. You can, however, send as many letters of support as you want from the following sources:</p><ul><li>Citizens of Australia;</li><li>Organizations in Australia; and</li><li>Individuals or organizations in your field of expertise who are internationally recognized.</li></ul><p>It is unnecessary to have a nominator when submitting your EOI to the GTIP. Still, your EOI improves if you include a completed Form 1000 identifying an appropriate nominator. You can modify your nominator by submitting an EOI and lodging the DTV application. You will not be allowed to change nominators once you have submitted your DTV application with a completed Form 1000.</p><p><strong>Application Process&nbsp;</strong></p><p>One can submit an Expression of Interest (EOI) to the Department of Home Affairs if users believe users meet all conditions. The Department may invite people to apply for this visa after completing this. You will be given a unique identity and encouraged to apply for a Global Talent visa if one is selected. A visa application is then given top priority. Around 15,000 migration spots have been set up for this visa for the 2020-2021 year. So, how do people go about applying?</p><p><strong>Step 1: Fill Out the Expression of Interest Form</strong></p><p>One must submit an Expression of Interest (EOI) here external icon at this time. This information is forwarded to the Department of Home Affairs. The Department then provides travelers a unique Invitation reference identifier and invitation code if they match the program’s qualifications.</p><p><strong>Step 2: Fill Out a Visa Application</strong></p><p>Step 1 completed? Apply for a Global Talent (Subclass 858) visa if you are in or outside of Australia at the time of your application. Apply for a visa using one ImmiAccountexternal icon after receiving an invitation reference identity and invitation code.</p><p><strong>Expense</strong></p><ul><li>$4,110 for the principal applicant</li><li>$1,030 for a dependent (under the age of 18).</li><li>$2,055 dependent (over the age of 18)</li></ul><p><strong>Conclusion</strong></p><p>Australia, London, San Francisco, Singapore, Taipei, and Washington, DC all have Global Talent Officers. They engage with potential applicants, businesses, and industries to promote the program. Contact us for further information. ​​​</p><p><br>&nbsp;</p>', 'the-pathway-to-global-talent-visa', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1658998573_11964.png', 1, '2022-07-28 18:56:13', '2022-07-28 18:56:13'),
(15, 'TR Visa and Does it Allow to Sponsor Parents in Australia', 'TR Visa and Does it Allow to Sponsor Parents in Australia', 'The Temporary Graduate Visa (subclass 485), commonly TR, allows students (overseas students) to work and reside in Australia for a particular time after', 'TR Visa and Does it Allow to Sponsor Parents in Australia', NULL, 0, '<h4>Introduction</h4><p>The Temporary Graduate Visa (subclass 485), commonly TR, allows students (overseas students) to work and reside in Australia for a particular time after completing their studies. Holding this visa, one could travel, work, and study in Australia.</p><p>Graduates may apply for the Temporary Graduate Visa (subclass 485) just once as the principal candidate. However, the visa can only be obtained for six months after completing the course.</p><p><strong>Systematic Eligibility of TR visa</strong></p><ul><li>be under the threshold of 50</li><li>possess an eligible visa</li><li>having had a student visa in the previous six months</li><li>Having just completed a CRICOS-registered course</li><li>Nominate just one visa stream – it is impossible to alter visa streams after applying.</li></ul><p><strong>How much time does it take to acquire a temporary resident visa?</strong></p><p>Users can apply for the TRV three months before they want to travel, as the procedure takes an average of 90 days to complete. This will also provide applicants with adequate time to recover passports.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The benefits of a TR visa are that The Temporary Resident Permit application permits foreign nationals to enter the Nation for a set period. For example, a Temporary Resident Permit’s expiration length might range from one day to three years, depending on why they need to enter Canada.</p><p><strong>Parent Visa (Permanent)</strong></p><p>The Parent Program enables Australian citizens or permanent residents to sponsor adult children for permanent residency in Australia.</p><p>The Parent visa migration program is capped and queued; certain visa classes have a 30-year processing delay. Therefore, the application will be handled in the order received.</p><p><strong>Primary requirements</strong></p><ul><li>Parent of citizenship or continuous resident</li><li>The candidate must be the parent of an Australian citizen or residency permit who has lived in Australia for at least two (2) years.</li><li>The appliers must satisfy the balance of family test (at least half of the applicants’ children and step-children must be Australian citizens or permanent residents, or more of the prominent people who applied’ children must be settled permanent citizens or residents of Australia than just about any other single nation).</li><li>Onshore applications for non-contributory and contributory parent visas require the primary applicant to be 66 or older. To submit an onshore parent application, individuals must be of retirement age in Australia. As shown below, the pension age will progressively rise from 66 to 67 years old.</li></ul><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Period within which a person was born</td><td>Pension Age</td><td>Changes</td></tr><tr><td>From 1 July 1955 to 31 December 1956</td><td>66 years and 6 months</td><td>1 July 2021</td></tr><tr><td>From 1 January 1957 onwards</td><td>67 years</td><td>1 July 2023</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><ul><li>Assurance of support (AoS) – Applications for a permanent Parent category visa require an AoS, a formal commitment from an individual or organization to provide financial assistance to the candidate so that they do not rely on social security benefits.</li></ul><p>TR visas allow you to bring family parents without sponsorship or PR by utilizing Visitor visas (temporary).</p><p><strong>Access for visitors (Temporary)</strong></p><p>A permanent parent visa may be financially out of reach for several people, while non-contributory access may be impractical due to lengthy processing timeframes.</p><p>A visitor visa may be a quick and inexpensive way to bring parents to Australia to spend time with relatives. Parents of Australian permanent residents and citizens can presently use the Visitor (Subclass 600) visa stream to spend time with their children, allowing lengthier stays of up to 12 months in 18 months. Parents of Australian permanent residents and citizens can get longer-term visiting visas.</p>', 'tr-visa-and-does-it-allow-to-sponsor-parents-in-australia', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1658999362_823554.png', 1, '2022-07-28 19:09:23', '2022-07-28 19:09:23'),
(16, '6 Things to Know About Australian Grading System', '6 Things to Know About Australian Grading System', 'When you first come to know about the Australian grading system, itâ€™s super different from what you are used to having in the UK or USA.Â  The Australian', '6 Things to Know About Australian Grading System', NULL, 0, '<h3><strong>Introduction</strong></h3><p>When you first come to know about the Australian grading system, it’s super different from what you are used to having in the UK or USA.&nbsp; The Australian grading system is undeniably one of the ‘may or may not be weird’ grading system. But is it really weird or is it not weird? Here’s 6 things to know about the Australian grading system.</p><h3><strong>Number 1: High school Grading System</strong></h3><p>Even though every state and territory has their own grading system, in high school most of the grades fall between A to F.&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Grade Score</strong></td><td><strong>Grade Description</strong></td><td><strong>Grade&nbsp;</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>85-100</strong></td><td>Excellent</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td><strong>75-84</strong></td><td>Good</td><td>B</td></tr><tr><td><strong>51-69</strong></td><td>Satisfactory</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td><strong>31-50</strong></td><td>Limited</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td><strong>26-30</strong></td><td>Very Low</td><td>E</td></tr><tr><td><strong>0-25</strong></td><td>Fail</td><td>F</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><h3><strong>Number 2: Diverse University Grading System</strong></h3><p>Now comes the university grading system in different cities. Even though there’s a common grading system in universities in Australia, universities in different cities follow different different grading systems like schools do.</p><p><strong>Australian Capital Territory</strong></p><p>Top Universities: University of Canberra, Australian National University, Charles Sturt University, UNSW Canberra, Australian Catholic University&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Grade Score</strong></td><td><strong>Grade Description</strong></td><td><strong>Grade&nbsp;</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>85-100</strong></td><td>Extremely High Standard of Achievement</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td><strong>75-84</strong></td><td>High Standard of Achievement</td><td>B</td></tr><tr><td><strong>50-69</strong></td><td>Acceptable Standard of Achievement</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td><strong>25-49</strong></td><td>Limited Standard of Achievement</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td><strong>0-24</strong></td><td>Very Limited Performance</td><td>E</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>New South Wales</strong></p><p>Top Universities: The east coast state, New South Wales, houses the University of New South Wales, University of Sydney, University of Newcastle, Macquarie University and La Trobe University. &nbsp;</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Grades</strong></td><td><strong>Grade Description</strong></td><td><strong>Grade Scale (%)</strong></td></tr><tr><td>HD</td><td>High Distinction</td><td>85-100</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>Distinction</td><td>75-84</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>Credit</td><td>65-74</td></tr><tr><td>P</td><td>Pass</td><td>50-64</td></tr><tr><td>F</td><td>Fail</td><td>0-49</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>Northern Territory</strong></p><p>Top Universities: Charles Darwin University and Flinders University.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Scale 2</strong></td><td><strong>Scale1</strong></td><td><strong>Grade&nbsp;</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>17-20</strong></td><td>5</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td><strong>14-16.99</strong></td><td>4-4.99</td><td>B</td></tr><tr><td><strong>11-13.99</strong></td><td>3-3.99</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td><strong>8-10.99</strong></td><td>2-2.99</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td><strong>0-7.99</strong></td><td>1-1.99</td><td>E</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>Queensland</strong></p><p>Top Universities: University of Queensland, Bond University, Griffith University and James Cook University.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Grades</strong></td><td><strong>Grade Description</strong></td><td><strong>GPA</strong></td></tr><tr><td>HD</td><td>High Distinction</td><td>7.00</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>Distinction</td><td>6.00-6.99</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>Credit</td><td>5.00-5.99</td></tr><tr><td>P</td><td>Pass</td><td>4.00-4.99</td></tr><tr><td>F</td><td>Fail</td><td>1.00-3.99</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>South Australia</strong></p><p>Top Universities: University of South Australia, University of Adelaide, Torrens University.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Grade</td><td>Grade Name</td><td>Grade Scale</td></tr><tr><td>HD</td><td>High Distinction</td><td>85-100</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>Distinction</td><td>75-84</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>Credit</td><td>66-74</td></tr><tr><td>P1</td><td>Pass Level 1</td><td>55-64</td></tr><tr><td>P2</td><td>Pass Level 2</td><td>50-54</td></tr><tr><td>F1</td><td>Fail Level 1</td><td>40-49</td></tr><tr><td>F2</td><td>Fail Level 2</td><td>30-39</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><h3><strong>Number 3: The Honors grading system</strong></h3><p>Honors degree comes with its very own grading system. Honors degree in Australia is generally a one year qualification taken after an undergraduate degree and involves further study in a particular discipline area.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Grades</strong></td><td><strong>Grade Description</strong></td><td><strong>Grade Scale (%)</strong></td><td><strong>GPA</strong></td><td><strong>UK Equivalent</strong></td><td><strong>US Equivalent</strong></td></tr><tr><td>HD</td><td>High Distinction</td><td>85-100</td><td>7.00</td><td>First Class</td><td>A+</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>Distinction</td><td>75-84</td><td>6.00-6.99</td><td>Second Class- Upper Division</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>Credit</td><td>65-74</td><td>5.00-5.99</td><td>Second Class- Lower Division</td><td>B</td></tr><tr><td>P</td><td>Pass</td><td>50-64</td><td>4.00-4.99</td><td>Third Class</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td>F</td><td>Fail</td><td>0-49</td><td>0.00-3.99</td><td>Fail</td><td>F</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><h3><strong>Number 4: GPA- ATAR Story</strong></h3><p>&nbsp;Universities in Australia don’t even commonly use GPA [sum of (grade point x credit point)÷ sum of credit points] except for in medicine and law stream subjects . Instead they use ATAR (Australian Tertiary Admission Ranks). ATAR is more of a ranking system than a grading system.&nbsp;</p><h3><strong>Number 5: UK-US Comparison</strong></h3><p>Despite its totally different grading system it’s not much difficult to decode it in the UK or US grading system.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Grades</strong></td><td><strong>Grade Description</strong></td><td><strong>Grade Scale (%)</strong></td><td><strong>GPA</strong></td><td><strong>UK Equivalent</strong></td><td><strong>US Equivalent</strong></td></tr><tr><td>H1</td><td>First Class Honor</td><td>80-100</td><td>7.00</td><td>First Class</td><td>A+</td></tr><tr><td>H2A</td><td>Second Class Honor(Division A)</td><td>75-79</td><td>6.00-6.99</td><td>Second Class- Upper Division</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td>H2B</td><td>Second Class Honor(Division B)</td><td>70-74</td><td>5.00-5.99</td><td>Second Class- Lower Division</td><td>B</td></tr><tr><td>H3</td><td>Third Class Honor</td><td>65-69</td><td>4.00-4.99</td><td>Third Class</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td>P</td><td>Pass</td><td>50-64</td><td>&nbsp;</td><td>&nbsp;</td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>F</td><td>Fail</td><td>0-49</td><td>0.00-3.99</td><td>Fail</td><td>F</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td><td>&nbsp;</td><td>&nbsp;</td><td>&nbsp;</td><td>&nbsp;</td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><h3><strong>Number 6: Top 5 University</strong></h3><ul><li>University of Melbourne ( follows grading system of Victoria)</li><li>Monash University ( follows grading system of Victoria)</li><li>University of Sydney ( follows grading system of North South Wales)</li><li>The University of Queensland ( follows grading system of Queensland)</li><li>University of North South Wales ( follows grading system of North South Wales)</li></ul><p>&nbsp;Some cities do follow the European grading system but it is their own grading system that has set them apart. It might be a little heavy to comprehend at first but you get the hang of it in no time.</p>', '6-things-to-know-about-australian-grading-system', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1658999544_267446.png', 1, '2022-07-28 19:12:25', '2022-07-28 19:12:25'),
(17, 'Australia COVID-19 Update for International Bangladeshi Students', 'Australia COVID-19 Update for International Bangladeshi Students', 'The coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak has wreaked havoc on people&#039;s daily lives throughout the world. Universities have had to make significant modifications to', 'Australia COVID-19 Update for International Bangladeshi Students', NULL, 0, '<h3><strong>Introduction</strong></h3><p>The coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak has wreaked havoc on people’s daily lives throughout the world. Universities have had to make significant modifications to their activities, with many closing early and altering their teaching methods.</p><p>&nbsp;Many universities welcome applications from people from all over the world. However, your ability to study abroad will be determined by the limitations of both the country you wish to study in and your home country. Although it is a difficult time for individuals considering studying abroad, universities are nonetheless eager to welcome international students. Universities are working hard to limit the impact of the pandemic by putting in place measures.</p><p>Every educational establishment has its unique set of procedures, so if you know where you want to study, double-check them. Most colleges will continue to actively recruit international students and will make alternative arrangements if you are unable to go when the term starts.</p><p>For the remaining few months of the 2019/20 academic year, many universities continued to teach by giving lectures and tutorials online. Some universities, such as The University of New England and The University of South Australia, have announced that they will continue to offer online teaching for mass lectures in 2020/21, although small group teaching will be done as much as feasible in person. Every university has implemented a psychical class for the students&nbsp;as of 2022.</p><p>Australia has become one of the popular destinations for Bangladeshi students to pursue higher study.</p><p><strong>Latest number of Bangladeshi student’s enrollment and commencement in Australian education system as per 2021:</strong></p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Sector</strong></td><td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Some of Data YTD Enrolments</strong></td><td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Some of Data YTD(Year to date) commencements</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Year</td><td>2018</td><td>2019</td><td>2020</td><td>2021</td><td>2018</td><td>2019</td><td>2020</td><td>2021</td></tr><tr><td>Higher Education</td><td>5,637</td><td>5,921</td><td>5,622</td><td>4,694</td><td>1,922</td><td>1,776</td><td>1,370</td><td>974</td></tr><tr><td>VET</td><td>608</td><td>778</td><td>1,183</td><td>1,540</td><td>320</td><td>405</td><td>600</td><td>669</td></tr><tr><td>School</td><td>27</td><td>42</td><td>39</td><td>53</td><td>12</td><td>20</td><td>15</td><td>29</td></tr><tr><td>ELICOS</td><td>212</td><td>185</td><td>171</td><td>76</td><td>148</td><td>139</td><td>127</td><td>58</td></tr><tr><td>Non-Award</td><td>114</td><td>169</td><td>149</td><td>69</td><td>74</td><td>92</td><td>67</td><td>26</td></tr><tr><td>Grand Total</td><td>6,598</td><td>7,095</td><td>7,164</td><td>6,432</td><td>2,476</td><td>2,432</td><td>2,179</td><td>1,756</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;<strong>The covid situation in Bangladesh:</strong></p><p>Bangladesh recorded 1952362 Coronavirus Cases since the epidemic began, according to the World Health Organization (WHO). In addition, Bangladesh reported 29124 Coronavirus Deaths. (Source: World Health Organization)<br><strong>The covid situation in Australia:</strong></p><p>Total Coronavirus Cases in Australia<br>Daily new Coronavirus Cases in Australia<br>Daily Deaths Coronavirus Cases in Australia</p><p><strong>Travel information:</strong></p><p>Unless they are flight personnel, all travellers arriving in Australia by air should complete the Digital Passenger Declaration. A DPD can be started up to seven days before your flight, but it must be submitted before you leave for Australia. The DPD asks for information that is considered vital to one’s health. Passengers must show proof that the critical health information was filled out prior to boarding the plane. This is a legally binding necessity. A civil penalty (fine) of 30 penalty units (currently $6,660 AUD) may be imposed on anyone who fails to comply with the requirement. Section 46 of the Biosecurity Act of 2015 specifies this. Passengers who do not declare their intentions before boarding their trip may experience delays upon arrival in Australia.</p><p><strong>Agreements on the border</strong></p><p>Unvaccinated Australian citizens and permanent residents will be able to depart Australia without a travel exemption from April 18, 2022. Travellers entering or leaving Australia would no longer be required to take a negative pre-departure test, and cruise ships will be allowed to enter the country.</p><p>All incoming travelers must meet the testing and quarantine standards of the state or territory in which they arrive, as well as every other state or territory to which they intend to travel.</p><p>Visa cancellation, detention, and removal may be considered for international visitors who arrive in Australia without completing vaccination requirements and without an exemption.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Education in Australia for international students:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Australia is currently the third most popular destination for international students in the English-speaking world, behind the United States and the UK. Many international students choose to study in Australia because of the cultural diversity, friendly natives, and quality of education.</p><p><strong>If a student aspires to study in Australia in the future, he or she must be prepared with the following items:</strong></p><ul><li>Find a good education provider and a course that you would like to study.</li><li>Read the institution’s website carefully for all the information you’ll need to make an informed decision, such as a description of the course offered, the setting, the teaching techniques, the facilities, and the minimal English language proficiency, among other things.</li><li>Examine the true costs of learning, as well as the applicable rules and regulations governing job, housing, and other areas of daily life.</li><li>Check that the institution and the course being pursued are officially registered with the Australian government at http://cricos.education.gov.au/ and <a href=\"http://www.studyinaustralia.gov.au/\">www.studyinaustralia.gov.au</a>.</li></ul><p><strong>Choosing an education agency entails the following steps:</strong></p><ul><li>After you’ve decided on an institution and a course, go to the course’s website and register for it. If a student is having trouble enrolling, he or she can seek assistance from approved agents. Please inquire for a list of the institution’s authorized education agents.</li><li>Visit www.pieronline.org to see if the agent has completed the Education Agents Training Course. Qualified agents will be well-versed in Australia’s educational system, visa procedures, and way of life.</li><li>Consult friends or others who are known to have studied or are known to have studied in Australia.</li></ul><p><strong>When dealing with an education agent, read all of the procedures thoroughly before signing a contract with the agent.</strong></p><ul><li>Do not sign the formal agreement or pay any money to the agent if you are unhappy with any of the terms.</li><li>Carefully read the course charge, length of study, and return policy if you do not wish to continue working with this agent in the future. 4. Ensure that you are aware of all of your rights, including the refund arrangements.</li><li>&nbsp;Make sure you get a copy of the written agreement as well as any other documents you sign.</li></ul><p><strong>Student Visa:</strong></p><p>You can find more information about student visa here</p><ul><li><a href=\"https://immi.homeaffairs.gov.au/visas/getting-a-visa/visa-finder/study\">https://immi.homeaffairs.gov.au/visas/getting-a-visa/visa-finder/study</a></li></ul><p><strong>Insurance for Health:</strong></p><ul><li>As an international student, having Overseas Student Health Cover (OSHC) for the duration of your studies in Australia is a requirement of your student visa. Visit www.oshcworldcare.com.au for more information. The student’s health insurance should last for the duration of his or her schooling.</li></ul><p><strong>Vaccines we recognize for the purpose of travel to Australia</strong></p><p>As of 17 January 2022, we recognize the following vaccines for the purpose of travel to Australia:</p><ul><li>Coronavac (Sinovac)</li><li>Covishield (AstraZeneca – Serum Institute of India)</li><li>BBIBP-CorV for people under 60 years of age on arrival in Australia (Sinopharm China)</li><li>Covaxin (Bharat Biotech)</li><li>Sputnik V (Gamaleya Research Institute)</li></ul>', 'australia-covid-19-update-for-international-bangladeshi-students', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1658999678_962708.png', 1, '2022-07-28 19:14:38', '2022-07-28 19:14:38');
