(24, 'The Step-by-Step Guide to Understand Australian Student Visa Extension as an International Studentï¿¼', 'The Step-by-Step Guide to Understand Australian Student Visa Extension as an International Studentï¿¼', 'Introduction', 'The Step-by-Step Guide to Understand Australian Student Visa Extension as an International Studentï¿¼', NULL, 0, '<p><strong>Introduction</strong></p><p>Although there is no automatic extension of a student visa in Australia, there are various circumstances in which an existing student’s visa can be extended. While the visa application is not difficult, it must be followed to the letter. If you wish to extend your student visa in Australia, keep reading to find out what you need to do to stay in the country and continue your experience!</p><p><strong>Why one might opt for a student visa extension in Australia?</strong></p><ul><li>You may need to extend your visa in one of four situations:</li><li>Extended research proposal</li><li>New academic program</li><li>Your post-graduate thesis has already been submitted; however, your visa will expire before the marking is completed.</li><li>For some reason, your course has been extended, and your visa will expire before you finish it.</li></ul><p>If you’re not sure which category you’re in or need assistance processing your application, please contact us.</p><p><strong>Requirements needed for visa extension</strong></p><p>You must apply for a new student visa before your existing one expires if you want to prolong your stay on a student visa. If you do not submit your application on time, you risk being deported, which could have an impact on future visa applications. Once you’ve decided that extending your student visa is the best option, you’ll need to get the following things in order:</p><p><strong>Enrollment Confirmation (CoE)</strong></p><p>The formal document from the educational institution is the Confirmation of Enrolment (CoE). The Certificate of Enrolment (CoE) contains information regarding the applicant’s enrollment status. The course duration, fees paid, and total fees owed are all included in this information. When applying for a student visa, this document is required. While studying in Australia, your CoE must be valid at all times, and cancellation may have an impact on your visa status.</p><p><strong>Language Requirements in English</strong></p><p>You’ll need proof of your English language abilities in the form of documents. This can be demonstrated by taking an IELTS or comparable test. You must submit your English language test results with your application.</p><p><strong>Student Health Insurance for Overseas Students</strong></p><p>All international students must have and maintain health insurance for the duration of their stay in Australia, according to the Australian government. You must keep your current Overseas Student Health Coverage (OSHC). OSHC does not renew itself and must be renewed to span the period of your new visa. The start and finish dates must correspond to the student visa. As a result, you must contact your healthcare provider and renew your coverage.</p><p><strong>Examine your health</strong></p><p>When applying for a student visa, you must undergo a medical examination. This shows that you are in excellent health to the Department of Home Affairs. You must submit documents with your application to show proof of the health checks. Your ImmiAccount will issue you a HAP number as well as a referral letter for a clinic that details all of the essential assessments.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Financial Prerequisites</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The application must show that you have the financial means to meet your expenses, including course fees, travel, and living expenses. This is accomplished by submitting employment documents as well as proof of your annual income and assets. There will also be a request for proof of true access to the requisite funds.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Documents needed for visa extension</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>When it comes to personal documentation, you’ll need to submit the following information to prove your identity:</p><ul><li>Certificate of Birth</li><li>Identity page of a passport (i.e. every page with visa sample &amp; immigration stamp)</li><li>Card of National Identification</li><li>Every page of the household registration book, as well as</li><li>A curriculum vitae (certified by the local authorities)</li><li>Certificate of Marriage (for married students)</li><li>Number of the OSHC Policy</li><li>HAP Identification Number</li><li>Proof of financial capability</li><li>Codes for Confirmation of Enrolment (CoE)</li></ul><p><strong>Process of student visa extension</strong></p><p><strong>Step 1: Register for the course</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Obtaining a fresh Confirmation of Enrolment (CoE) from your educational institution is the first step in the application process. It’s critical to allow time for the educational department to process this and return it to you. Processing timeframes vary, but they normally range from 5 to 10 days. This process can also be influenced by how quickly you pay your fees, as they will not be processed unless you do so. You will receive an email confirming your enrolment after all of the prerequisites have been satisfied and the fees have been paid (CoE).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Step 2: Set up Overseas Student Health Insurance (OSHC</strong></p><p>The next step in the procedure is to get your health insurance in order. Once you’ve confirmed that your health insurance is valid for the duration of your stay with the insurance provider, you can begin compiling all of the essential visa documents.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Step 3: Get your visa documents ready</strong></p><p>It’s vital to keep in mind that the list of required visa documents varies depending on your place of origin and the education provider you choose. As a result, each applicant’s checklist is unique. The document checklist tool on the Department of Home Affairs website, however, can help. It’s crucial to remember that the checklist is subject to change, so it’s a good idea to check the website for updates frequently.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Step 4: Meet the criteria for a Genuine Temporary Entrant (GTE)</strong></p><p>All student visas must meet the Genuine Temporary Entrant (GTE) criterion. The GTE lets the Department of Home Affairs determine whether or not the applicant is serious about studying in Australia. You must include a personal statement as part of this procedure to demonstrate that you are sincerely interested. The personal statement should include information about your life and how the course will benefit you in the future. This gives the candidate a chance to talk about their situation in their native country and their potential future if their student visa is approved. You should provide as many documents as possible to back up all of your points.</p><p><strong>Step 5: Apply for a student visa</strong></p><p>Submitting a student visa application with your Immi Account is the final step in the application process. To proceed, you must attach all essential documents and pay a charge. You can also hire a migration consultant to assist you with your online application. If you submitted your student visa application while onshore, the Department of Home Affairs will mail you a letter of acceptance along with a Bridging Visa (BVA). Check your nominated email address for any correspondence regarding the status of your application frequently. This can aid in a smooth and quick application process.</p><p><strong>Financial proof/fund for visa extension</strong></p><p>Depending on your visa category and country assessment, you may be required to produce proof of financial capabilities to continue studying in Australia. There are a variety of options available, including:</p><p><strong>Fund For Yearly Months</strong></p><p>This choice is appropriate if you intend to study for a further year or more. Evidence of money sufficient to pay your stay, tuition fees, and living expenses in Australia for the duration of your stay, which is usually 12 months. It also includes a travel itinerary that includes a trip return to Australia (about $1000- $1200), living expenses in Australia (approximately AUD$20,000–AUD 21,000), and a one-year tuition price for whichever subject and length of study you select.</p><p><strong>Annual Income Evidence</strong></p><p>If you want to participate in a short or long course, evidence of annual income from your sponsor, parent, spouse, or personal income is necessary for an Australian Student visa. It is estimated that it will cost around AUD 60,000.</p><p><strong>Waiver on student visa application by dept of home affairs</strong></p><p>If you had a student visa on or after 1 February 2020 and couldn’t finish your course within the original visa validity due to COVID-19’s effects, we will waive the visa application fee to allow you to file a new student visa application. This applies to you if you:</p><ul><li>you had to postpone your studies since you were unable to visit Australia due to travel restrictions.</li><li>were obliged to lower their academic burden to part-time</li><li>you weren’t able to finish your work-based training or placements</li></ul><p><strong>Conclusion</strong></p><p>If your visa is denied, more information may be needed. In this case, they will send you an email asking for more information. If your visa is merely denied, you will have the option of hiring a migration lawyer to challenge the decision. It’s vital to emphasize that this only applies to applicants for onshore visas.</p>', 'the-step-by-step-guide-to-understand-australian-student-visa-extension-as-an-international-studenti', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1659007090_377759.png', 1, '2022-07-28 21:18:10', '2022-07-28 21:18:10'),
(25, 'What is Adelaide like for international students', 'What is Adelaide like for international students', 'Adelaide, South Australiaâ€™s cosmopolitan coastal capital city isÂ home to 1.3 million (2016 stat) people and ranked 3rd in worldâ€™s most livable cities', 'What is Adelaide like for international students', NULL, 0, '<p>Adelaide, South Australia’s cosmopolitan coastal capital city is&nbsp;home to 1.3 million (2016 stat) people and ranked 3rd in world’s most livable cities (2021 economic intelligence unit’s global livability Index). The city is said to be the perfect place for studying and we have strong&nbsp;reasons to say so. Despite being small enough to get around, it has all the big city life advantages and is one of the least expensive cities with one of the highest standards of living. It’s a leading education city; got top universities with world class courses, full of wonders, warm welcomes, incredible foods, festivals, museums and churches with historical momentums. And with its Mediterranean climate you’ll get to enjoy hot &amp; dry summers and mild winters. Adelaide is a great choice for international students. You’ll have access to part time jobs that pays really well and the place is perfectly positioned just a short drive from some of Australia’s most unique regions. Here nothing is too far. It’s even nicknamed twenty minutes city as you can get anywhere in 20 minutes from here. South Australia offers you all- city, suburban and country life all in one place.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Summer</strong></td><td><p>Dec-Feb</p><p>&nbsp;25-35 degree</p><p>Hot &amp; Dry</p></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Autumn</strong></td><td><p>March-May</p><p>20-25 degree</p><p>Mainly Dry</p></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Winter</strong></td><td><p>June-August</p><p>9.1-14.5 degree</p><p>Cool- Wet</p></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Spring</strong></td><td><p>Sept-Nov</p><p>20-25 degree</p><p>Little rain</p></td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><br><br>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Living Cost:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>Living cost in Adelaide is 14% less than other major cities of Australia. Here transport fees start from 2.15 AUD. On arrival to settle in you’ll need access to around 3000 AUD (depending on rental cost and lifestyle). Other than that it will take 300-400 AUD per week to cover the living cost (also depending on lifestyle&nbsp;and rental). SAIBT estimates that a student would need approximately 14000-19000 AUD per year for accommodation, food, textbook, transport, entertainment, recreation and other personal expenses. The city has access to a whole range of restaurants, shops, Living places, and public transports with ease.&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Expense</td><td>Weekly</td><td>Monthly</td></tr><tr><td>Accommodation(shared or single)</td><td>AUD 120-380</td><td>AUD 480-1520</td></tr><tr><td>Groceries</td><td>AUD 90-130</td><td>AUD 360-520</td></tr><tr><td>Telephone/Internet</td><td>AUD15-40</td><td>AUD 60-160</td></tr><tr><td>Transport</td><td>AUD 20-40</td><td>AUD 80-160</td></tr><tr><td>Electricity/Gas</td><td>AUD 35-50</td><td>AUD 140-200</td></tr><tr><td>Clothes/Entertainment</td><td>AUD 50+</td><td>AUD 200+</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Total</strong></td><td>AUD 330-645</td><td>AUD 1320-2580</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><br><br>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>University and education opportunities:</strong></p><p>&nbsp;Australia is reputed for its world class education. The Education Index (UN’s human Development Index, 2018) listed Australia the 2nd highest in the world and Adelaide isn’t any different.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>–</strong><i>Top 4 Universities of Adelaide</i></p><ul><li>Torrens University (As the country’s fastest-growing university, Torrens University Australia brings a fresh approach to higher education and with globally recognized qualification you’ll be equipped to work anywhere in the world.)</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Flinders University (Flinders is ranked as the number one South Australian University for undergraduate teaching quality and student support.)</li></ul><p><br><br>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>University of South Australia (&nbsp;the&nbsp;<strong>University of South Australia</strong>&nbsp;is an open research institution that is associated with the Association of Commonwealth Universities, Australian Technology Network, and Universities Australia and is South Australia’s no.1 university for graduate career.)&nbsp;</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>University of Adelaide (The University is consistently ranked in the top 1% of the world’s university and is recognized globally as a leading research university.)</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Nearly 36000 international students from 120 countries around the globe are in South Australia among which 20000 are from Universities Living on and off city. You can get a Bachelor degree, Master’s degree or PhD in pretty much every subject including Business, art and media, public health and teaching. Even there’s option for great vocational education and English courses.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Job opportunities:</strong></p><p>&nbsp;The opal capital has many opportunities for part time jobs from a wide range of industries. You can do internships in industries related to your field of studies. This way you can earn and gain experiences for future stable jobs. Plus all thus is a great chance for exploring and collecting new skills. Students entitled to student Visa can earn a minimum of 19.49 AUD per hour both on and off campus and can work up to 20 hours a week.&nbsp;You can do Catering and hospitality business, retail and warehouse staff, office and retail cleaning industry, health and aged care, car wash and automotive industry, painting and construction, different office jobs and many more!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Application Process:</strong></p><p>The application process is simple but would require some preparation.</p><p><a href=\"https://www.studiesinaustralia.com/studying-in-australia/how-to-study-in-australia/applying-for-admission#1\">Step 1: Choose your course and education provider. Go through corses and find out what suits you and your career goal</a></p><p><br><a href=\"https://www.studiesinaustralia.com/studying-in-australia/how-to-study-in-australia/applying-for-admission#2\">Step 2: Apply</a>. Once you have figured out what you want to study, apply.</p><p><br><a href=\"https://www.studiesinaustralia.com/studying-in-australia/how-to-study-in-australia/applying-for-admission#3\">Step 3: Have your application processed. Gather all the required documents and everything needed for application process.</a></p><p><br><a href=\"https://www.studiesinaustralia.com/studying-in-australia/how-to-study-in-australia/applying-for-admission#4\">Step 4: Accept your offer.</a></p><p><br><a href=\"https://www.studiesinaustralia.com/studying-in-australia/how-to-study-in-australia/applying-for-admission#5\">Step 5: Prepare for departure</a>. Apply for your student visa, health insurance and accommodation.</p><p>Adelaide has established institutions across all areas of education. The universities rank in top 2% globally. People here live relaxed but vibrant life. It’s got-</p><ul><li>Great public transport system</li><li>Quality of life</li><li>Top notch universities</li><li>Affordability</li><li>Attractions</li><li>Food&nbsp;</li><li>Livability</li><li>Ten gigabit city</li><li>Great internship and employment opportunities</li></ul><p>And if you are looking for a chaos free vigorous life, Adelaide’s the perfect fit.</p>', 'what-is-adelaide-like-for-international-students', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1659007246_750618.png', 1, '2022-07-28 21:20:47', '2022-07-28 21:20:47'),
(26, 'What&#039;s Brisbane like for International Students', 'What&#039;s Brisbane like for International Students', 'In Australia Brisbane is the third biggest city and it is the capital of Queensland. There are numerous universities in Brisbane. Additionally, there are two', 'What’s Brisbane like for International Students', NULL, 0, '<p>In Australia Brisbane is the third biggest city and it is the capital of Queensland. There are numerous universities in Brisbane. Additionally, there are two main universities in Brisbane and those are: <strong>The University of Queensland</strong> and <strong>The</strong> <strong>Queensland University of Technology</strong>. Approximately, the growth of the students admitted in Brisbane has increased to 78,000 per year because of its educational services, standard of living and soothing beaches. However, the students should look at the costs of the courses to cut out the extra expenses, so students can also weigh up the costs offered by each university in Brisbane. In Brisbane, the universities offer some of the courses and those are:</p><ul><li>Law</li><li>Medicine</li><li>Marketing</li><li>Information and Technology</li><li>Biotechnology</li></ul><p>&nbsp;There are several benefits that the students receive:</p><ul><li>The universities in Brisbane offer financial benefits to the international students. The students .</li><li>As a student, the house rent is decreased, also electricity bills and internet bills are involved in the rent.&nbsp;</li><li>The students receive a 25% discount in the transportation costs.</li><li>In Brisbane, the groceries are less costly compared to other areas, so it is easy for the students to spend their money on groceries.&nbsp;</li><li>At low costs students are able to have meals, it costs $20.</li><li>The international students are also benefited with insurance that counterbalances the hospital bills, ambulance expenses, consultation with doctors.</li><li>In Brisbane, there are numerous beautiful sites to roam around like the lakeshore, Kangaroo bluff point and Art Galleries.&nbsp;</li></ul><p>The application form for international students would ask which courses he or she prefers although this question is asked to every student in Australia, not only international students. Either the international students can fill the application form online or by post. The international students should complete this application form as per the deadline. Many application forms ask about a student’s personal details like where he or she lives, guardian’s name and educational backgrounds. Also, the universities ask for your IELTS results to ensure about a student’s prowess in English. Additionally, they want to be certain about the academic qualifications a student holds like they can ask for a student’s O levels and A Levels certificates. Besides these, they want to ensure which course I prefer for my upcoming sessions. Although, the utmost information that the universities want to manifest is that the international students are employed. If he or she is already employed he or she has to fill up that question, however if he or she is unemployed then this is not a required question for the students. After the academic organization has received a student’s application, he or she will be apprised about the results. The students will receive a confirmation mail from the universities if his or her application is accepted by the authority. Also, the students are required to ensure that there is any condition given in the offered letter or not. If any condition is provided then the students must act accordingly.&nbsp;</p><p>In Australia, Brisbane is considered as the inexpensive city for the students to live there. International students can rent the houses at reasonable prices and the rented house includes bed, desk, shared washrooms, kitchens and store rooms. However, the costs may differ due to chosen rooms by the international students. There is a special discount for the Brisbane students that they would receive 25% discount on by bike. If the international students bring their own laptops or ipads then they are required only to think about their gadgets. International students can buy their stationeries from Officeworks and Kmart at low costs.&nbsp; The accommodations are provided on and off campus to the students by their respective universities. Those who provide accommodations to the students include the electricity bill, gas bill, water bill and internet bill in the rent. Students can also receive discounts simply by showing their student ID cards, these would reduce their costs on&nbsp; multiple products and services. The students would receive discounts on software and technology. On public transport, they would receive a discount. On entertainment sites, they would also get discounts on amusement parks, museums and movie tickets. On discount, the students can select restaurants and get discount prices on different types of foods and drinks such as beverages. Besides these, the students can get discount prices on hair stylist and they can choose any haircut they want on discount. When an international student migrates to Australia, he or she can choose to live in a shared house so the prices incurred would be less. There are two sites and those two sites are known as Flatmates and Flatmates Finders, the students can take the help of these sites to find their preferable shared house in Brisbane. Over Brisbane central business district and South Bank region, commercial accommodation is dispersed for the students. There are great opportunities for the students if the students desire to stop over the center of the city because of student accommodations.</p>', 'whats-brisbane-like-for-international-students', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1659008334_989229.png', 1, '2022-07-28 21:38:54', '2022-07-28 21:38:54'),
(27, '6 Reasons International Students Change Course | Apollo Intl', '6 Reasons International Students Change Course | Apollo Intl', '6 Reasons International Students Change Course', '6 Reasons International Students Change Courseï¿¼', NULL, 0, '<p><strong>6 Reasons International Students Change Course</strong></p><p>Australia, counting till 2018, has 8,69,709 international students studying in different universities all over the country. Australia has 43 universities (40 Australian, 2 International, and one private) and more than 22,000 courses. Popular in Australia are –</p><ul><li>Accountancy</li><li>Agricultural Science</li><li>Actuarial Science</li><li>Architecture</li><li>Biomedical Engineering</li><li>Core Engineering</li><li>Earth Science</li><li>Computer Science and Information Technology</li><li>Psychology</li><li>Tourism and Hospitality Management</li></ul><p>Sometimes, students decide to change their courses, and it’s normal. But it would help if you remembered that changing courses here in Australia is not a simple process as an international student.&nbsp;</p><p>Here are six reasons why international students change courses:</p><ul><li><i><strong>After studying for a while, you realized the course wasn’t as expected. </strong></i>You don’t find it as interesting as you did.<br>&nbsp;</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><i><strong>Found the course too hard. </strong></i>You are having a hard time understanding and getting it.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><i><strong>It wasn’t financially feasible to study this course.</strong></i> The course expenses exceeded your budget and capability, and bearing the cost is becoming burdensome.</li></ul><p><br>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><i><strong>I couldn’t generate the expected results.</strong></i> Fall behind on credits and can’t maintain good academic results.&nbsp;</li></ul><p><br><br>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><i><strong>Failed to see desired career prospects.</strong></i> The career choices don’t match your dream jobs or what you expect. Other courses have better-desired career prospects.</li></ul><p><br><br>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><i><strong>In case you prefer to study another course. </strong></i>You found your passion and interest in some other course and would like to devote your efforts to learning that.</li></ul><p><br><br><br>&nbsp;</p><p>For locals, the process is reasonably straightforward, but there’s a bit of work for international students. And there are a few things you must take into account.</p><p><br><br>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>You must have six-plus months of your courses completed because you’ll require the permission of your current education provider to transfer, and you won’t get it if you haven’t completed more than six months of the course unless you have strong reasons.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>&nbsp;If your end date of confirmation of enrollment changes with the change of your course, you’ll have to apply for a new visa within 28 days of completing your main course to avoid canceling your visa or leaving Australia.</li></ul><p><br><br>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>You’ll need to ensure that you’ve maintained good academic results, for many courses will only accept you if your GPA is at a certain level.&nbsp;</li></ul><p>Step by step guided way to a successful course change is explained below briefly:</p><ul><li><i><strong>Book an appointment with a student adviser</strong></i>. A student adviser will be able to guide you properly and reduce the chances of missed opportunities, financial distress, or student visa issues. That way, you’ll be able to go through all your options and choices, whether you’ll need to change institutions or just go for internal transfer and everything.</li><li><i><strong>Consider Visa requirements </strong></i>so that you don’t end up with a canceled visa or made to leave Australia.</li><li><i><strong>Understand your financial obligations</strong></i>. Check with your education counselor to go through your financial aid and scholarship options. Studying is costly and changing courses will add upon extra charges on you.</li><li><i><strong>Select a new course or institution.</strong></i> Do your research. See which institution or courses suit you and your interests to pursue the degree.&nbsp;</li></ul><p>Once you receive an offer, you can seek credit for a study you’ve already completed depending on the situation. It’s not a loss even if you change courses after 3 or 4 years. We don’t always know what we want or where our potential lies when we choose our courses in the first year. Through exploration is how we find the stage where we shine the brightest. So don’t hold back from following your passion and go for it. Do your research and weigh all the options and make choices for yourself.</p>', '6-reasons-international-students-change-coursei', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1659008512_612464.png', 1, '2022-07-28 21:41:52', '2022-07-28 21:41:52'),
(28, 'Accredited and Non-Accredited Universities in Canadaï¿¼', 'Accredited and Non-Accredited Universities in Canadaï¿¼', 'Accreditation refers to deciding if a college meets specific standards and achieves the missions it claims to have. The accreditation system in Canada is a', 'Accredited and Non-Accredited Universities in Canadaï¿¼', NULL, 0, '<p>Accreditation refers to deciding if a college meets specific standards and achieves the missions it claims to have. The accreditation system in Canada is a bit different. According to the council for higher education (CHEA), accreditation reviews the quality of higher education institutions and programs. This can entail an institution or just a specific academic program. Accreditation agencies were originally formed to ensure the transferability of credits between institutions. However, it has many subparts as it directly affects various aspects of an institution and a student’s academic journey. Now, what exactly are Accredited and Non-Accredited Universities?</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><i><strong>Accredited</strong></i> means that the university or education institution has been certified that the institution meets specific standards and can fulfill its mission. It’s a way of telling that the institution is legit and worth your money, time, and effort. <i><strong>Non-Accredited</strong></i> means that the university hasn’t been checked by experts for its authenticity and may or may not be worth your money, time, and effort. In Canada, each province and territory is responsible for every educational institution inside it, and they oversee the accreditation process. In Manitoba, the Department of Advanced Education handles the process. There’s no federal accreditation in Canada. However, some universities seek evaluation from American regional accreditation agencies. To confirm if an educational institution is recognized and accredited, you’ll have to contact your provincial or territorial student financial aid authority.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><i><strong>The core difference between the two:</strong></i></p><p>Accredited &nbsp; – &nbsp; When you are in an accredited university, there’s no questioning its standard of education, methods, skills they equip you with, its validity in the market, and authenticity. You will be eligible for federal government aid and loans. There is no risk of getting rejected by the government or other big corporations.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Non-Accredited – In Non-Accredited universities, there are no federal government loans or aid, so you’ll have to pay from your pocket or depend on private aiding organizations.</p><p>&nbsp;Unless your institution is accredited, some organizations don’t allow you to apply for a permit. The institution might be a scam, and their education and programs might not be legit. If you ever transfer to another school, credit transfer to accredited universities would not be possible.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><i><strong>Benefits of Accredited Universities:</strong></i></p><ul><li><strong>Financial Eligibility: </strong>according to CHEA, to seek to offer federal financial aid, the school must be accredited. Only schools that meet those standards and have been certified as authentic can get the benefits with no exception.</li></ul><p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Academic Rigor:&nbsp;</strong> The academic requirements and course contents are reviewed and ensured to be met by an external curriculum.&nbsp;</li></ul><p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Up-to-Date Knowledge and skills: </strong>with accreditation, the quality of education, its relevancy, and currency are guaranteed. It means academic programming- the tools and resources used- is updated with industry standards and best practices.&nbsp;</li></ul><p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p><ul><li><strong>The faculty reputation </strong>helps to determine an institution’s positive reputation, including the expertise of its faculty members demonstrating expertise in their field and among peers.</li></ul><p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p><ul><li><strong>&nbsp;Employment Opportunities: </strong>Many employers require graduates to be from accredited schools or programs. Some industries require specific certifications or licensure, and accreditation can make a difference in taking these exams or completing additional application requirements. Plus, having an accredited school listed on a resume could distinguish among candidates.</li></ul><p><br><br>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><strong>Student Service Support:</strong>&nbsp;<strong> </strong>If a school is accredited, it is evident that students’ support meets standard requirements. Having access to a library and other resources is often required to be accredited.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Going to an accredited school isn’t a must to thrive in the future. Great renowned schools aren’t accredited but are a plus point for you. Depending on the plan, the accreditation of your school will affect your student life like if you want to get a Ph.D., not being from an accredited school might create problems.</p>', 'accredited-and-non-accredited-universities-in-canadai', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1659008664_291863.png', 1, '2022-07-28 21:44:27', '2022-07-28 21:44:27'),
(29, 'Co-op vs non-co-op Courses in Canada', 'Co-op vs non-co-op Courses in Canada', 'Co-op education means cooperative education. This education allows students to work in a department that is correlated to their degree. This assists a student', 'Co-op vs non-co-op Courses in Canada', NULL, 0, '<p>Co-op education means cooperative education. This education allows students to work in a department that is correlated to their degree. This assists a student in achieving the goals in their career. It also fills the education expenses and gets a job with a high payment amount after graduation. If a student carries on with their co-op course, the course’s teacher will ease them into an organization that is unfortunately not gained by most students. An alternative process for this course is that the students will do schooling for four months, and for the next four months, they will be underemployed in a packed schedule. Many tertiary institutions offer co-op courses to the students besides their education. In Boston, the Northeastern University students only have the co-op selection for five years vs. four years.&nbsp;</p><p>Within these five years, they have experience working for 1.5 years and a job with a good salary.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>There are ten advantages to taking a co-op course:</strong></p><ul><li>Co-op courses give the students the benefits of having an idea about the job as per their degree.&nbsp;</li><li>The students can also apply this hypothesis and law in their real-life work scenarios.&nbsp;</li><li>Co-op courses assist the students in flourishing their merchantable skills to prosper in different marketplaces.&nbsp;</li><li>By doing the co-op courses, students are benefited from obtaining approximately two years of worthwhile experiences.</li><li>Taking this course helps a student build a relationship with co-workers and expand their network with future managers.&nbsp;</li><li>This co-op course assists the students in bearing the expenses of daily life and paying the semester fees.</li><li>This course helps the students to inspect various work environments and courses of action for the future.</li><li>Also, students are aware of their skills and strengths while working in the corporate world.</li><li>The students must make a research-based career document to hold up their studies and job inquiry.&nbsp;</li><li>It assists a student in renovating the skills for their career and mastering themselves by calling for a job interview.&nbsp;</li></ul><p><strong>However, besides the benefits, there are also negative impacts of taking co-op courses.</strong></p><ul><li>The duration would be longer for a student to complete their desired degree.</li><li>The work pressure can be challenging for the students besides their studies.&nbsp;</li><li>Some of the courses are proposed at times, so more organizations must determine which degree would be suitable for a student.</li><li>By including co-op courses, the expenses are done by the students would increase for this course.</li><li>The students are likely to be transferred to other areas for work.</li><li>However, there is no commitment to achieving the co-op position.</li><li>A student is not bound to get a job after graduation.&nbsp;</li></ul><p><strong>Although, there are some conditions to apply for this course.</strong></p><ul><li>A student must have permission to study validity.</li><li>In Canada, a work placement is required for the students to conclude their study programs.&nbsp;</li><li>There should be approval from the authority for the students to complete their work placements to receive their degrees.</li><li>The co-op courses would require 50% or fewer expenses than the study.&nbsp;</li></ul><p><strong>There are 11 best Canadian Universities in total that offer co-op courses.</strong></p><ol><li>University of Waterloo</li><li>University of British Columbia</li><li>University of Victoria</li><li>University of Ottawa</li><li>University of Quebec</li><li>Centennial College</li><li>Simon Fraser University</li><li>Wilfrid Laurier University</li><li>University of Alberta</li><li>University of Toronto</li><li>University of Calgary</li></ol><p>Additionally, internships are entirely different from co-op courses. Within co-op courses, the students are associated with the university and employers. At the same time, an internship represents only the correlation between employers and students.&nbsp;</p><p>On the other hand, internships are part-time work, while co-op courses are full-time work. Internships are frequently unpaid. However, co-op courses are paid primarily. Also, as per non-co-op courses, the students must attend schooling from the beginning to the end. The difference between co-op and non-co-op courses is that co-op courses allow the students to continue their semesters for four months, and for the next four months, they will continue with their work. On the other hand, non-co-op courses allow the students to continue their studies.</p>', 'co-op-vs-non-co-op-courses-in-canada', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1659010781_159458.png', 1, '2022-07-28 22:19:41', '2022-07-28 22:19:41'),
(30, 'How Canadian Grading System Varies According to Provinceï¿¼', 'How Canadian Grading System Varies According to Provinceï¿¼', 'The grading system in Canada varies depending on the state, university, and type of education (elementary, secondary, and tertiary).', 'How Canadian Grading System Varies According to Provinceï¿¼', NULL, 0, '<p>The grading system in Canada varies depending on the state, university, and type of education (elementary, secondary, and tertiary).</p><p>According to the province:</p><p>&nbsp;Before initiating the application process for tertiary education in Canada, most international students want to know about the grading system. It is critical to understand that the grading system used in Canadian higher education institutions differs from that used in other countries. Each of Canada’s ten provinces has its grading system, and there are schools in both regions.</p><ul><li>Alberta &amp;</li><li>Quebec</li></ul><p><strong>The grading system in Alberta:</strong></p><p>The Alberta territory includes the well-known universities like:</p><p>The University of Alberta&nbsp;</p><p>MacEwan University&nbsp;</p><p>The King’s University&nbsp;</p><p>Concordia of Edmonton&nbsp;</p><p>The University of Calgary&nbsp;</p><p>Ambrose University&nbsp;</p><p>Mount Royal University</p><p>St. Mary’s University</p><p>Burman University</p><p>All of which adhere to the same academic grading system as mentioned above. The Alberta grading system is as follows, with some minor variations:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Letter Grade</strong></td><td><strong>Percentage</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>A+</strong></td><td>90-100%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>A</strong></td><td>95-89%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>A-</strong></td><td>80-84%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>B+</strong></td><td>77-79%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>B</strong></td><td>73-76%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>B-</strong></td><td>70-72%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>C+</strong></td><td>67-69%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>C</strong></td><td>63-66%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>C-</strong></td><td>60-62%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>D</strong></td><td>55-59%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>D</strong></td><td>50-54%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>F</strong></td><td>0-49%</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>The grading system in Quebec:</strong></p><p>To be far more specific, McGill University, University de Montreal, University de Quebec, Bishop’s University, Concordia University, University Laval, University de Sherbrooke, Sir George Williams University, and Loyola College are among the universities in Quebec that use the same grading system.</p><p>Students from any university in Quebec can pass the exams if they answer 60 percent or 64 percent of the questions correctly. As a result, we can conclude that the passing grade is “C,” as indicated by the above percentage. However, with the help of professors, a C in the range of 56-59 percent is possible. Consult the table below to understand this province’s grading system with clarity.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Letter Grade</strong></td><td><strong>Percentage</strong></td><td><strong>Description</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>A+</strong></td><td>95-100%</td><td>Exceptional&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td><strong>A</strong></td><td>90-94%</td><td>Outstanding</td></tr><tr><td><strong>A-</strong></td><td>85-89%</td><td>Excellent</td></tr><tr><td><strong>B+</strong></td><td>80-84%</td><td>Very Good</td></tr><tr><td><strong>B</strong></td><td>75-79%</td><td>Good</td></tr><tr><td><strong>B-</strong></td><td>70-74%</td><td>Average</td></tr><tr><td><strong>C+</strong></td><td>65-69%</td><td>Satisfactory</td></tr><tr><td><strong>C</strong></td><td>60-64%</td><td>Pass</td></tr><tr><td><strong>C-</strong></td><td>55-59%</td><td>Low Pass</td></tr><tr><td><strong>D</strong></td><td>0-54%</td><td>Fail</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>British Columbia’s grading system:</strong></p><p>In British Columbia, the only certainties in life are death, taxes, and the letter F, which denotes failure.</p><p>Yes, even faculties within the same university may use different grading systems when converting letter grades to percentages.</p><p>Royal Roads University in British Columbia offers excellent online master’s degrees.</p><p><br><br>&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Letter</strong></td><td><strong>Percent</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>A</strong></td><td>86–100%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>B</strong></td><td>73–85%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>C+</strong></td><td>67–72%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>C</strong></td><td>60–66%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>C−</strong></td><td>50–59%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>F (fail)</strong></td><td>0–49%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>I (incomplete)</strong></td><td>0–49%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>W</strong></td><td>withdrawn</td></tr><tr><td><strong>P</strong></td><td>Passed</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Here,</p><p>I = Incomplete – Missing assignments</p><p>F = Fail – Received grade under 50%</p><p>W = the student has withdrawn from this course</p><p>P = the student has passed this course though a grade is unavailable (usually when switching schools/grading systems, i.e., moving from the US).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Saskatchewan grading system:</strong></p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Letter</strong></td><td><strong>Percent</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>A+</strong></td><td>90–100%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>A</strong></td><td>80–89%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>B</strong></td><td>70–79%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>C</strong></td><td>60–69%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>D</strong></td><td>50–59%</td></tr><tr><td><strong>F</strong></td><td>0–49%</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Most subjects are divided into three competencies at the high school level in Saskatchewan. Marks are normally shown as numbers on report cards, and an average of the two marks associated with the subject is calculated. &nbsp; For instance, if a student receives A, A, and B+ grades in a topic, teachers will compute an average of the three grades (in this case, 85 percent).</p><p><strong>The grading system in Manitoba:</strong></p><p>In Manitoba, the primary grading system is based on a student’s GPA, so the formula has to be ingrained in your memory more than that catchy song you once heard on the radio.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Letter grade</strong></td><td><strong>Grade point value</strong></td><td><strong>&nbsp;</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>A+</strong></td><td>4.5</td><td>Exceptional</td></tr><tr><td><strong>A</strong></td><td>4.0</td><td>Excellent</td></tr><tr><td><strong>B+</strong></td><td>3.5</td><td>Very good</td></tr><tr><td><strong>B</strong></td><td>3.0</td><td>Good</td></tr><tr><td><strong>C+</strong></td><td>2.5</td><td>Satisfactory</td></tr><tr><td><strong>C</strong></td><td>2.0</td><td>Adequate</td></tr><tr><td><strong>D</strong></td><td>1.0</td><td>Marginal</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Fail</strong></td><td>0.0</td><td>Failure</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Pass</strong></td><td>Pass</td><td>Pass</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>In Canada, what is a 4.0 GPA?</strong></p><p>Almost every Canadian university employs a combination triangle in the grading system, beginning with letter grades and progressing to percentages and GPAs, but this is not universal across the country. You can only get an answer to your question if you know which state you want to study in because the Canadian GPA varies slightly from one university’s territory to the next. However, in Canada, the commonly known GPA or Grade Point Average ranges from 0.00, which denotes the lowest grade, F, to 4.00, which denotes the highest grade, A.</p><p><br><br>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Well, how to determine GPA before applying to a Canadian University:</strong></p><p>To make this process easier, international students need to be aware that the GPA used in Canadian universities differentiates from the GPA used in other states. Most countries have a GPA of 5.0, while others may have a GPA as high as 20. Regardless, Canadian universities use a variety of grading systems and different GPA criteria.&nbsp;</p><p>Many students are frightened that their GPA will not be enough to get them into a good school. Before enrolling in any Canadian university, you should calculate your GPA and see if you meet the requirements.</p><p>To do that, you must use the GPA Formula, which is:</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>GPA= Total Grade Points earned multiplied by the credit hours for each course.</strong></td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', 'how-canadian-grading-system-varies-according-to-provincei', 'admin/image/blog/thumbnail/blog_1659011568_888322.png', 1, '2022-07-28 22:32:49', '2022-07-28 22:32:49');
